His fame as a poet began with the publication, prior to B.C. 35, of the Ecloycce or Bucolica, ten brief poems, imit-ating the pastoral poetry of Theocritus the Syracusan (3rd cent. Rc.) Like all the great works of Vergil, these are written in hexameters, and it was the smoothness of the versification and the novelty of the subject which gained them their popularity.
